00:01.200 --> 00:10.020
Okay, Paul, the tape's rolling. One comment I wanted to make to you, I was going
to ask you if you'd seen the Wall Street Journal article that Peter Dubois wrote

00:10.020 --> 00:22.120
about... I've been waiting for it, but I haven't seen it yet. Do you have any
way to get a copy of it? I think that David at Timescape is going to send me a

00:22.120 --> 00:31.160
copy, and ultimately I'll find it in the library, I guess. If you have easy
access to the copy, I'd love to have one. Okay, well, I've got one. I'll send it

00:31.160 --> 00:41.340
to you. In fact, I wrote him a letter the day that I read it, and he called me
at work when he got the letter, and he said that he got turned on to Dick by

00:41.340 --> 00:49.940
your article in Rolling Stone, and he asked me specifically to say hello to you
and thank you for getting him turned on to Phil K. Dick. Isn't that great? Wow,

00:50.000 --> 00:58.360
that's very nice to hear. He was flattered that somebody read it in Wall Street
Journal and wrote him a fan letter, and I thought it was kind of interesting

00:58.360 --> 01:04.760
that Wall Street Journal would even have something about Phil Dickin, and I was
kind of blown away by that. He was really very nice. I talked to him quite a

01:04.760 --> 01:14.120
while, and he said to say hi to you. Well, that's great. What's his name,
Dumris? Dubois, D-U-B-O-I-S, two words. That's my pronunciation. I don't

01:14.120 --> 01:24.740
remember how he pronounced it. That's right. But I can send you a copy of it.
That's no problem. That's really nice. I got a phone call today from Phil's

01:24.740 --> 01:36.900
editor and my friend David Hartwell at Timescape, and he said that Confessions
of a Crap Artist is already being reordered. There's demand for a second

01:36.900 --> 01:44.020
printing. It's selling much, you know, even though it's a small printing, it's
selling much better than expected, and that they think the Wall Street Journal

01:44.020 --> 01:56.920
article is playing a significant part in that. Well, good deal. I hope people
learn more about him. Okay, the interview that I constructed is a little looser

01:56.920 --> 02:05.260
than when I generally talk to authors, so we'll just probably meander around a
little bit, so bear with me. What I'll first of all ask you is, how did you

02:05.260 --> 02:24.960
become acquainted with Phil Dick? I met Phil at the notorious Oakland World
Science Fiction Convention in 1968 at the old Claremont Hotel. And I had been

02:24.960 --> 02:40.760
turned on to his work really less than a year before that by some people who are
kind of well known in the comics field, Trina Robbins and Artie Spiegelman, Bob

02:40.760 --> 02:52.580
Stewart. And I wrote about Phil's writing and particularly a book I was reading
at the time, which was The Game Players of Titan, in an underground newspaper

02:52.580 --> 03:09.220
called Avatar. And so when I met Phil briefly at this convention, even though we
were both out of our minds because of various stimuli uh I gave him a copy of

03:09.220 --> 03:21.220
the underground paper with a story about him and uh I guess it excited him as
well because it was some you know beginning of some kind of uh recognition other

03:21.220 --> 03:32.940
than you know a few letters and so forth for what he was doing and at that time
I was just about to move out to California so we saw each other several times

03:32.940 --> 03:50.240
like again partly through mutual friends, in and around 1959, the beginning of
1970. And in 1969, I had the occasion which is recorded somewhere in balance.

03:52.060 --> 04:03.020
For a brief, bad period, I was Timothy Leary's campaign manager, when he had
just been released from the original threat of going to jail by winning a

04:03.020 --> 04:15.380
Supreme Court victory that caused, you know, over a thousand other people to be
released within the same week. The victory was that you couldn't be made to say

04:15.380 --> 04:26.560
that to pay the tax on marijuana because of self-incrimination. At any rate,
Larry got out of jail or out of the threat of it, decided to run for governor,

04:26.740 --> 04:36.880
had me be his campaign manager, and we went across the country and ended up in
Montreal visiting John and Yoko where they were having their bed in for peace.

04:38.020 --> 04:50.340
And from John Lennon's hotel room, I found out from Tim actually while we were
traveling, I'd bought UVic, which had just come out in hardcover. And Tim Leary

04:50.340 --> 05:00.540
turned out also to be a tremendous fan of Philip Dick and Ron at this time.
Really, not very many people knew of him. except really diehard science fiction

05:00.540 --> 05:14.680
fans. Leary had read a lot of his work, and so from Lennon's Hotel Suite in
Montreal, we called Phil, I think on Lennon's nickels, and he got the chance to

05:14.680 --> 05:27.560
rap with Tim Leary, telling him what a great fan he was for a half an hour. So
this basically is one of the funny standout incidents, particularly for Phil of

05:27.560 --> 05:29.260
our early connection.

05:32.160 --> 05:42.320
It was during these years that he was still struggling along and getting all
these niggardly advances and had very low prestige, as you say, except for the

05:42.320 --> 05:50.920
hardcore science fiction fans. Why did he keep it up during those years? Even
into the late 70s, he was struggling and not making very much money yet. What

05:50.920 --> 06:05.800
kept him going? When I think a real commitment, first of all, to the ultimate, I
don't know if I want to say seriousness, but that's really it. A real commitment

06:05.800 --> 06:17.420
to what he was creating and what he wanted to say, that always when he's
written, it's been because he had to write. And it was equally true that it

06:17.420 --> 06:27.480
became the only way he could make a living. It's a classic freelance writer
situation where even though you're... Okay, if you only get $1,500 for a science

06:27.480 --> 06:37.060
fiction novel, then what you have to do to stay alive is write $6,000 a year,
which he came pretty close to doing at one point.

06:40.320 --> 06:56.060
He, I think, did not want to go back and start working in a record store again
or basically give up on his career as a writer, it was not until early in the

06:56.060 --> 07:07.860
1960s that he gave up trying to become a successful mainstream writer. And even
then, he didn't give up. Although it felt like that to him at the time, he just

07:07.860 --> 07:17.580
put it away on the back burner, having tried very, very hard for 10 years. The
first 10 years in which, while he had his first 10 or so science fiction novels

07:17.580 --> 07:28.000
published. He wrote a mainstream novel for every science fiction novel he wrote.
So, really, he was writing two novels for one thousand dollar advance, one of

07:28.000 --> 07:37.800
which would be published in an A-suffle novel, and the other of which would go
from publisher to publisher and just be turned down. And there are still ten or

07:37.800 --> 07:44.100
eleven thousand unpublished novels. Any chance they'll ever get published, do
you think? I think that it's inevitable.

07:46.360 --> 08:01.820
They'll had mixed opinions about their quality and I haven't read most of them
but it it seems clear although we may be surprised that there's nothing as

08:01.820 --> 08:13.260
polished or as good as Confessions of the Craft Artist which I think is actually
one of his five or six best books but because of the interest in Phil's work it

08:13.260 --> 08:26.220
seems inevitable at this point that one way or another they will most or
probably all be published within the next 10 or 20 years but probably still by

08:26.220 --> 08:31.400
small publishers not by New York publishers

08:34.460 --> 08:44.380
when I was making up my questions I noticed now that a lot of them have to do
with what he wrote about and I consequently wanted to ask you a question Was he

08:44.380 --> 08:53.680
really that way? Did he really believe that? And so this is kind of the first
one of those. They may tend to get repetitive, but in all of his works, there's

08:53.680 --> 09:03.700
a mistrust of the senses, of what the senses are telling us, a mistrust of
reality. And he seems to be saying that the truth comes in glimpses every once

09:03.700 --> 09:12.440
in a while and that our senses can't really see it. It's kind of revealed to us.
Did he really live by that? Was that his philosophy, day-to-day life, or was

09:12.440 --> 09:27.580
that just his writing style? Yes, that was unquestionably a part of his daily
lifestyle. I don't know if I would call that aspect of it a philosophy, although

09:27.580 --> 09:41.020
he definitely had one, but it was a very real part of his perception. And I
spoke of the seriousness of his work. I think that a primary purpose, if not the

09:41.020 --> 09:59.280
only one, has always been, as a Sagittarius, to pierce through the superficial
reality around us of what only appears to be real and to get at what is really

09:59.280 --> 10:16.280
real in his view. So everything that he wrote was an attempt to do that. And in
his daily life, a

10:16.280 --> 10:24.000
lot of issues that would come up that you or perhaps he would describe as being

10:24.000 --> 10:26.520
at least partly indicative of a paranoid personality.

10:29.320 --> 10:42.240
But he somehow had an incredible sense of humor. and often wisdom about it or
ability to see himself that made him on the one hand one of the craziest people

10:42.240 --> 10:54.280
that most of his friends ever knew and on the other hand it's just great to have
as a friend

10:57.560 --> 11:09.600
In one interview he said that you had accused him of being pre-cognitive. Were
you serious when you suggested this? That's interesting. I don't know if I ever

11:09.600 --> 11:25.560
saw that interview. I think that was in Science Fiction Review. Uh-huh. Oh,
yeah. Yeah, I'm sure that I said something. Probably he was referring to

11:25.560 --> 11:38.680
something in the Rolling Stone piece although I'm not sure, even though he had
lots of private conversations it's likely that that that's what it was. He

11:38.680 --> 11:49.500
himself probably more strongly than I believe that at least in some ways that he
had incidents of being precognitive.

11:52.660 --> 12:08.260
And I think a good fictional illustration of that is the kind of theme that he
has of a man sitting in a city and suddenly seeing himself as a very old man 30

12:08.260 --> 12:09.420
years from now or whatever.

12:13.460 --> 12:28.060
He still used science fiction as a way of disguising actual reality so that it
would be palatable. But he was definitely describing the horrors and humorous

12:28.060 --> 12:37.380
fascination of a world that in almost every case is very real to him. In some
ways, he can take less of his books fairly literally.

12:40.120 --> 12:49.680
Was he labeled a science fiction writer only because that's the only category
that seemed to fit what he wrote, or was he really truly a science fiction

12:49.680 --> 12:58.660
writer? I guess it just depends on one's definition. Well, he was truly a
science fiction writer, and I think that the primary meaning of that is that you

12:58.660 --> 13:10.780
belong to the club and you learn by reading science fiction. And he came up
writing stories for all the science fiction magazines and then he started

13:10.780 --> 13:25.100
writing novels for Don Wollheim at Ace and was read only by science fiction
readers and was certainly aware of, as a fan, as a leader, all the science

13:25.100 --> 13:40.000
-fictional plotting devices and the whole concept of the genre, the sense of,
you know, does it matter who reads science fiction? And I think that that's what

13:40.000 --> 13:51.820
it means to be a science-fiction writer in a lot of ways is to come up from that
world and to stay within that world to whatever degree, at least with part of

13:51.820 --> 14:05.620
your work. And he definitely did that. He wasn't necessarily satisfied with
that, and that's easy to understand. But he did, although he's not a great

14:05.620 --> 14:15.820
reader of it after adolescence or whatever, he really loved science fiction, and
the people he wrote for and the people that he communicated with We're all

14:15.820 --> 14:27.040
pretty much in that room. At least, yeah, I think it diversified more in the
last 10 years. But still, I would consider him very squarely a science fiction

14:27.040 --> 14:38.440
writer. More so, say, than Bradbury. If there's any reason to make comparisons
to him, I'd consider Bradbury, in the end, a science fiction fantasy writer too.

14:41.420 --> 14:51.220
In your conversations with him, was he ever one to bemoan the fact that science
fiction is in this ghetto and the mainstream critics don't like it and that sort

14:51.220 --> 15:01.420
of thing? Or was he pretty much content just to write it and let other people
worry about that? He cared about those things. He always had a very kind of self

15:01.420 --> 15:16.400
-deprecating or humble attitude towards his work, while at the same time always
giving you to know somehow that he really took it as seriously and respected it

15:16.400 --> 15:22.480
as much as his most guarded fans. What I'm saying is that he really knew how
good it was.

15:25.640 --> 15:40.960
But he was able to be very humble about it. Now let's see the question that you
asked again. Oh, as far as science fiction being ghettoized, did he bemoan that

15:40.960 --> 16:03.920
fact? He bemoaned it in the sense that he felt that he and other writers in the
field that he respects deserved wider attention. and he would play on, if

16:03.920 --> 16:17.800
somebody was concerned about ghettoization, he could give the lifelong interview
on the subject as anybody. What frustrated him, and he was very frustrated by

16:17.800 --> 16:30.140
it, was primarily that he didn't have the freedom to write what he called
experimental mainstream novels as well. And of course, it was a tremendous

16:30.140 --> 16:42.060
victory for him. Finally, posthumously, but he was aware of it before he died,
when the transmigration of Timothy Archer was published, in hardcover, to the

16:42.060 --> 16:45.920
first publisher that he submitted it to after writing the novel and so forth.

16:49.380 --> 17:01.560
Or actually, before writing the novel. So, it was something that he always
wanted to do, to write this kind of book. The ghettoization of him as a science

17:01.560 --> 17:04.940
fiction writer kept him from him for a long time.

17:08.460 --> 17:19.940
One of his strangest books, according to a lot of people, and I've known several
people who can't read it, is The Three Stigmata of Palmer Eldritch. I've read

17:19.940 --> 17:28.240
interviews where Dick said he had never taken acid before he wrote the book, and
he says that you verified this. He said he took it, and then he read the proofs.

17:29.040 --> 17:40.760
And it scared him. Can you enlighten us on that? Is that pretty much the way it
happened? It's true that he had never taken LSD or, I think, any psychedelic

17:40.760 --> 17:51.120
drugs before he wrote the three stigmata of Palmer Eldridge. He had had
experience with amphetamines.

17:52.560 --> 18:08.040
and as for then taking LSD and reading the galleys that's possibly true except
that it was years before he read the galleys and maybe years before he took the

18:08.040 --> 18:16.920
trip onto them but he was he was afraid of it before he read them he was he
always claimed anyway too scared to read the galleys when they sent them to him

18:18.280 --> 18:26.360
and he didn't finally re-read the novel again according to what he always
claimed until a number of years later.

18:29.600 --> 18:40.620
But I'm sure there's no question that it scared him. It scared him while he
wrote it. At one point he told an interviewer that he wrote it to kind of

18:40.620 --> 18:52.500
exercise a terrifying vision of the man with the stigmata that he was seeing in
the sky while driving to the shack on the California coast that he was doing his

18:52.500 --> 19:05.880
writing. And that was very real to him and terrifying while he was writing it as
well as while reading it. I think, by the way, that it's a brilliant novel. Oh

19:05.880 --> 19:14.960
yeah, it's either number two or number three for me. I still haven't sorted it
all out, but it's been about seven years since I read it too.

19:17.920 --> 19:33.180
I guess probably his best-known novel, Until of Late, maybe, was The Man in the
High Castle. And there he used the I Ching before that became famous. Now, it

19:33.180 --> 19:42.860
came out in 1962. I didn't read it until 1973, but I guess that blew a lot of
people away who really hadn't heard of the I Ching and that sort of thing. And

19:42.860 --> 19:56.520
later he apparently repudiated the I Ching. Yes. Yes, I, uh... He did, in
several interviews, and he stopped using it. Since I originally was introduced

19:56.520 --> 20:08.320
to the itching by Phil's book and by someone else who had learned about it from
Phil's book. And still, he has the itching. I never took Phil's repudiation very

20:08.320 --> 20:22.880
seriously, but he did have the experience that many people have that, uh... the
book. The oracle eventually told him that it wasn't useful for him to keep

20:22.880 --> 20:38.500
asking questions of it. His feeling of what he said was that it was actually
trying to steer him in some wrong fashion. But I think that that kind of

20:38.500 --> 20:46.000
incidental effect of the man in the high castle of introducing the Chinese He's
supposed to change it to so many people who then introduced it to the whole

20:46.000 --> 20:55.420
culture. It's very fascinating. Yeah, I think he said he finally quit it because
it was trying to set him up.

20:58.260 --> 21:08.960
Right. Well, he felt that way about a lot of things. I read that he liked the
scanner darkly a lot and that he considered, at the time he wrote that, he

21:08.960 --> 21:17.940
considered it a masterpiece. And then I read that he only made about $3,500 off
of it, and that was in the late 70s. He was still getting screwed then, huh?

21:20.280 --> 21:30.860
Well, yes, although there's some element of distortion there. I mean, it's
certainly true that the book didn't get recognized, get as just desserts. I

21:30.860 --> 21:40.040
personally was involved in trying to find another hardcover publisher for it,
and I took it to one of the best, who was expected to be sympathetic, and they

21:40.040 --> 21:51.300
could make Hethertale's book. And ultimately, Double Day, who those unsatisfied
with, ended up publishing it. He couldn't find another publisher. And later,

21:51.620 --> 22:02.300
Bantam was unable to find any hardcover publisher for Valance. So this continued
right through his career until the very end when he had the satisfaction of

22:02.300 --> 22:12.600
having The Divine Invasion and Tim and the Archer come out in hardcover. So
yeah, that was very frustrating, And the amounts of money involved up through,

22:12.600 --> 22:16.800
well,

22:16.920 --> 22:29.300
ballots, but particularly Scanner, were very small. However, by that time,
Phil was doing very well indeed. In fact, he had sort of started to do pretty

22:29.300 --> 22:41.000
well, at least by his standards, during a period where he was still demonizing
to reviewers what a terrible business science fiction was. because he kept

22:41.000 --> 22:49.700
expecting that the money that was suddenly coming in would dry up and blow away
any day now, and he'd be back to the usual poverties because he was still only

22:49.700 --> 23:00.300
getting $2,000 or whatever for each book. But what actually started happening
was because of the quality of his work and the incredible vision that he has,

23:00.480 --> 23:11.640
and this has happened to other American writers. Charles Bukowski is an
interesting current example. Bill was very popular and very widely respected in

23:11.640 --> 23:25.540
other countries, particularly France, England, Japan, Germany, the Scandinavian
countries, Italy, and on and on, long before he had any kind of reputation in

23:25.540 --> 23:42.420
the United States except as the Hugo-winning author of Man in the High Castle.
otherwise popular paperback he authored. And that popularity abroad brought him

23:42.420 --> 23:46.620
to a point in the 1960s where suddenly he was earning

23:49.100 --> 24:04.560
first, say, over $15,000 a year, and then pretty quickly more than that on a
consistent basis with more than half of it coming from foreign rights to his

24:04.560 --> 24:16.580
work. And of course what had happened is he'd been a very prolific author as
well and already by this time he had, say, 20 or 25 books behind him and all the

24:16.580 --> 24:25.680
time he'd be getting $100 or $200 for this one or that one for this year's
royalty earnings in this country and they'd be translated into 20 different

24:25.680 --> 24:36.740
languages. and it added up to quite a good income so that if you took any one of
his books and could magically go back over its whole history you'd find out that

24:36.740 --> 24:47.160
most of the books that he wrote ended up earning him quite a fair amount of
money over the course of his whole life and if he'd carried it on into his

24:47.160 --> 24:57.160
estate that's certainly a lot of money by the end of the century so that a book
that may have sold for $1,500 ultimately over the years brought in $20,000 or

24:57.160 --> 25:08.480
$30,000 or $40,000 and there's more to come. And of course the two of them now
are bringing in that movie money. So there's kind of a paradoxical situation

25:08.480 --> 25:19.840
there. But the success that he did have in his later years financially certainly
completely came both from the quality of his work and from the incredible hard

25:19.840 --> 25:31.440
work that he'd done for so many years while he was starving which resulted in
him having a large body of guns. Nobody wants to die at the age of 53, God

25:31.440 --> 25:42.460
knows, but anybody would be proud to have the 50 books that Philip Deick wrote.
How do you account for his popularity in other countries, whereas he never

25:42.460 --> 25:49.220
really caught on that much until recently here? I think that this has happened
to quite a few

25:51.900 --> 26:11.320
very good and very original American writers that in a way a person like Phil,
his vision is so strong and really so American that it is difficult for people

26:11.320 --> 26:21.500
to appreciate here when it's first articulated but in Europe or in Japan And
they'll read these novels and say, my god, you know, here's somebody who's

26:21.500 --> 26:33.980
really talking about America. This really has the flavor of the real thing.
They're impressed because it cuts through cultural assumptions and all that to

26:33.980 --> 26:47.460
really paint a very powerful picture of the place and time that the author lives
in. And that's really missing from a lot of writers who might be more popular in

26:47.460 --> 26:59.320
their own country at their own era because their work, however good it is in
various respects, is also more palatable. It isn't as demanding in terms of,

26:59.460 --> 27:10.160
it's like a prophet, like a biblical prophet who's simply standing up and
telling you the truth about what's really going on in this culture and in this

27:10.160 --> 27:24.460
world and is usually stoned or ignored for telling the truth. At the distance, I
think, of Europe or Asia it was much easier to appreciate the brilliance and

27:24.460 --> 27:38.300
humor and intense insight with which Phil Dick was telling the truth in these
novels whereas it was only for the hardcore fans here in the United States.

27:40.180 --> 27:49.880
Okay, his last five novels or okay, let's put it this way, his last five science
fiction novels that were published, counting Transmigration as a science fiction

27:49.880 --> 27:58.880
novel, starting with Flow My Tears, but really then more with The Scanner
Darkly, but then really the last three, Valles, Divine Invasion, and

27:58.880 --> 28:08.620
Transmigration. That was something really different, totally different from
anything we'd seen before. Apparently he had a change of life or saw some

28:08.620 --> 28:16.460
visions or something that really made him open this up. Do you perceive this as
something new in him, or was this just a logical conclusion of where he'd been

28:16.460 --> 28:30.240
going to all the time? Well, it is certainly something new. I mean, he in fact
saw these three books, these last three books as a kind of a trilogy, even

28:30.240 --> 28:41.680
though they have different settings and subjects. The thematic material is
extremely related and it comes out of his own personal experiences and one sort

28:41.680 --> 28:55.740
of mystical experience in particular and also out of at least six years of
really intensive research into theology and philosophy and in many ways, you

28:55.740 --> 29:08.620
know, the spiritual history of human beings at least over the last 5,000 years
or so, which he just totally immersed himself in, originally on the pretext that

29:08.620 --> 29:17.500
he was doing research forroughs, which ultimately turned out to be true. But,
and there was a period of about three or four years where he didn't write a

29:17.500 --> 29:31.680
novel, and we all wondered if he would again. And I'm sure he wondered. So that
this extraordinary work, particularly the last three books, definitely, as you

29:31.680 --> 29:38.280
say, comes from a change of life, although not in the sense of going

29:38.280 --> 29:40.400
down to the church and getting religion.

29:42.940 --> 29:57.720
there was an awakening in him brought about as exactly as he describes in
Valleys by an incident I guess in 1975

30:01.360 --> 30:18.220
where he's sitting in his car in a very Southern California town Santa Ana or
Fullerton around there and is kind of zapped by this pink phosphine light, and

30:20.460 --> 30:33.480
nothing was really the same again after that, but he spent a couple of hours in
a really very subtle kind of other world, and it was only his sense of the

30:33.480 --> 30:43.400
importance of this experience that really gives it its way. In other words,
exactly what he went through, somebody else might have shrugged off who didn't

30:43.400 --> 31:00.560
have his particular powers of perception and interest. But he became obsessed
with the revelations that he had around and his questions about what was that

31:00.560 --> 31:13.020
happened to him and why. And ultimately, his answers which in effect are his
answers, and in this sense it's a culmination of his entire work, his answers to

31:13.020 --> 31:28.520
tentative or whatever, to all the questions he's been asking in all his books.
What is reality? What is history? What's really going on? And why? What is the

31:28.520 --> 31:39.260
real nature of the forces here? And as somebody quoted Einstein as saying,
Einstein was asked if he could A reporter asked him, what would you say if you

31:39.260 --> 31:45.900
